019f1-3d443 | 2026-06-29T10:28:27Z | session:019f12ce-2569-72e0-b959-6d87d5daec5d | User: it seems like the identity of agents (each specific/different instance) are not really treated as different agents from the moment they are created and instead we're deciding at the edges what gets signed with what key and what session is what agent --- I keep finding issues that should not exist if there were no confusion of what pubkey is what agent.... is this the case? \n  \n Assistant: I’ll answer from the live code, not from intent. I’m going to trace the identity path from session creation through engine/status/chat/who so we can distinguish “born-right identity” from “edge-time signer selection.” \n  \n Assistant: Yes. The current code is halfway corrected, but your diagnosis is basically right. \n  \n There is now an attempt to make sessions “born right”: `session_start` selects an ordinal signer before writing the session row, and `sessions.agent_pubkey` is written with that selected pubkey. That part is good. \n  \n But the actual identity is still not modeled as one first-class thing. It is split across: \n  \n - `sessions.agent_slug` \n - `sessions.agent_pubkey` \n - `identities.pubkey/base_pubkey/ordinal/session_id` \n - in-memory `session_keys` \n - `EngineParams.agent_slug` \n - `EngineParams.agent_label` \n - `EngineParams.agent_pubkey` \n - `EngineParams.keys` \n - `EngineParams.session_keys` \n  \n So many edges still reconstruct identity policy locally. \n  \n Concrete examples from live code: \n  \n - `runtime::status_for` signs status with the selected key/pubkey, but still labels the `AgentRef` with `p.agent_slug`, not `p.agent_label`. That means an ordinal identity can publish as pubkey `claude1` while semantically saying slug `claude`. \n - `publish_agent_reply` gets `from_pubkey` from `keys_for_session`, but builds the chat `AgentRef` with `rec.agent_slug`, again mixing selected pubkey with base slug. \n - `status_publish::status_from_session` builds status from `rec.agent_pubkey` and `rec.agent_slug`, which assumes the session row has already been perfectly reconciled. \n - `who` and `statusline` re-query `identities` to recover the ordinal label instead of receiving a single authoritative `AgentInstanceIdentity`. \n  \n That is exactly the pattern you described: the system has “which session is which agent?” and “what key signs this?” decisions distributed at the boundaries. \n  \n The direction I’d push is: make the created session carry one authoritative identity object from birth, something like: \n  \n ```rust \n struct AgentInstanceIdentity { \n     base_slug: String, \n     display_slug: String, // claude, claude1 \n     base_pubkey: String, \n     pubkey: String, \n     ordinal: u32, \n     signing_keys: Keys, \n } \n ``` \n  \n Then `Session`, `EngineParams`, status, chat, who, statusline, membership checks, and resume routing should consume that identity, not recompute it. There should be no normal callsites asking “do I use base keys or session keys?” or “do I display slug or ordinal label?” after session creation. That policy belongs at identity allocation time.
